ge reveals that allusions in musical writings to optical technologies reflect their spread from fairgrounds and laboratories into public consciousness and a range of discourses, including that of music. She demonstrates how concrete points of intersection—composers’ treatments of telescopes and peepshows in opera, for instance, or a shadow-play performance of a ballad—could then fuel new modes of listening that aimed to extend the senses. An illuminating look at romantic musical practices and aesthetics, this book yields surprising relations between the past and present and offers insight into our own contemporary audiovisual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMixed media (Music)y18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMixed media (Music)y19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and technologyxHistoryy18th century. 0aMusic and technologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aJoseph Haydn.  aLudwig van Beethoven.  aaudiovisual culture.  alistening.  aromanticism.  avisual technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022633709840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226337128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226337128/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles